#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "A Word About Configuration And Some Options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:66
msgid ""
"By default, LXD will allocate the required system memory, disk space, CPU "
"cores, etc., to the container. But what if we want to be more specific? That "
"is totally possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:68
msgid ""
"There are trade-offs to doing this, though. For instance, if we allocate "
"system memory and the container doesn't actually use it all, then we have "
"kept it from another container that might actually need it. The reverse, "
"though, can happen. If a container is a complete pig on memory, then it can "
"keep other containers from getting enough, thereby pinching their "
"performance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:70
msgid ""
"Just keep in mind that every action you make to configure a container _can_ "
"have negative effects somewhere else."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:72
msgid ""
"Rather than run through all of the options for configuration, use the tab "
"auto-complete to see the options available:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:78
msgid "and then hit TAB."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:80
msgid ""
"This shows you all of the options for configuring a container. If you have "
"questions about what one of the configuration options does, head up to the "
"[official documentation for LXD](https://linuxcontainers.org/lxd/docs/master/"
"instances/) and do a search for the configuration parameter, or Google the "
"entire string, such as \"lxc config set limits.memory\" and take a look at "
"the results of the search."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:82
msgid ""
"We will look at a few of the most used configuration options. For example, "
"if you want to set the max amount of memory that a container can use:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test limits.memory 2GB\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:88
msgid ""
"That says that as long as the memory is available to use, in other words "
"there is 2GB of memory free, then the container can actually use more than "
"2GB if it's available. It's a soft limit, in other words."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test limits.memory.enforce 2GB\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:94
msgid ""
"That says that the container can never use more than 2GB of memory, whether "
"it's currently available or not. In this case it's a hard limit."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test limits.cpu 2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:100
msgid ""
"That says to limit the number of cpu cores that the container can use to 2."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:102
msgid "!!! note"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "    When this document was rewritten for Rocky Linux 9.0, the ZFS repository for 9 was not available. For this reason all of our test containers were built using \"dir\" in the init process. That is why the example below shows a \"dir\" instead of \"zfs\" storage pool.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:106
msgid ""
"Remember when we set up our storage pool in the ZFS chapter? We named the "
"pool \"storage,\" but we could have named it anything. If we want to look at "
"this, we can use this command, which works equally well for any of the other "
"pool types too (as shown for dir):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc storage show storage\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:113
msgid "This shows the following:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:114
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  source: /var/snap/lxd/common/lxd/storage-pools/storage\n"
"description: \"\"\n"
"name: storage\n"
"driver: dir\n"
"used_by:\n"
"- /1.0/instances/rockylinux-test-8\n"
"- /1.0/instances/rockylinux-test-9\n"
"- /1.0/instances/ubuntu-test\n"
"- /1.0/profiles/default\n"
"status: Created\n"
"locations:\n"
"- none\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:131
msgid ""
"This shows that all of our containers are using our dir storage pool. When "
"using ZFS, you can also set a disk quota on a container. Here's what that "
"would look like setting a 2GB disk quota on the ubuntu-test container. You "
"do this with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config device override ubuntu-test root size=2GB\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:137
msgid ""
"As stated earlier, you should use configuration options sparingly, unless "
"you've got a container that wants to use way more than its share of "
"resources. LXD, for the most part, will manage the environment well on its "
"own."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:139
msgid ""
"There are, of course, many more options that may be of interest to some "
"people. You should do your own research to find out if any of those are of "
"value in your environment."
msgstr ""
